# Week 6 – Git Hands-on Summary

## Overview

In this week, I learned and implemented the fundamental Git concepts required for source code management. The hands-ons covered Git configuration, repository creation, file tracking, `.gitignore`, branching, merging, merge conflict resolution, and synchronizing changes with a remote GitHub repository.


# Hands-on 1 – Git Configuration and Basic Git Commands

## Objective

* Configure Git on the local machine.
* Integrate Notepad++ as the default Git editor.
* Create a local Git repository.
* Add files to source control.

## Activities Performed

* Verified Git installation using the Git version command.
* Configured the global Git username and email.
* Verified Git configuration.
* Created a local project named **GitDemo**.
* Initialized the project as a Git repository.
* Created a file named **Welcome.txt**.
* Added the file to the staging area.
* Committed the file to the local repository.
* Verified the repository status and commit history.
* Configured a remote GitHub repository for future synchronization.

## Git Concepts Learned

* Git installation verification
* Git configuration
* Repository initialization
* Working directory
* Staging area
* Local repository
* Git add
* Git commit
* Git status
* Git log
* Remote repository configuration



# Hands-on 2 – Using .gitignore

## Objective

Learn how to ignore unnecessary files and folders from Git tracking.

## Activities Performed

* Created a **log** folder.
* Created a sample log file.
* Created a **.gitignore** file.
* Configured Git to ignore:

  * All `.log` files
  * The entire `log` folder
* Verified that ignored files were not tracked.
* Added and committed the `.gitignore` file.

## Git Concepts Learned

* .gitignore
* Ignoring unnecessary files
* Preventing unwanted files from entering the repository
* Clean repository management



# Hands-on 3 – Branching and Merging

## Objective

Learn how Git branching works and merge feature branches into the main branch.

## Activities Performed

* Created a new branch named **GitNewBranch**.
* Switched to the new branch.
* Created **BranchFile.txt**.
* Added content to the file.
* Committed the changes.
* Switched back to the **main** branch.
* Compared differences between branches.
* Merged **GitNewBranch** into **main**.
* Verified commit history.
* Deleted the merged branch.

## Git Concepts Learned

* Branch creation
* Branch switching
* Feature branch development
* Git merge
* Git diff
* Commit history visualization
* Branch deletion



# Hands-on 4 – Merge Conflict Resolution

## Objective

Understand how Git handles merge conflicts and learn conflict resolution.

## Activities Performed

* Created a new branch named **GitWork**.
* Added **hello.xml** with specific content.
* Committed the file in the branch.
* Switched back to the **main** branch.
* Created another **hello.xml** with different content.
* Committed the changes.
* Compared branch differences.
* Attempted to merge **GitWork** into **main**.
* Observed a merge conflict.
* Resolved the merge conflict manually.
* Committed the resolved version.
* Updated the **.gitignore** file to ignore backup files.
* Committed the updated `.gitignore`.
* Deleted the merged branch.
* Verified commit history.

## Git Concepts Learned

* Merge conflict
* Conflict resolution
* Manual merge
* Three-way merge concept
* Merge commit
* Repository cleanup



# Hands-on 5 – Clean Up and Push to Remote Repository

## Objective

Learn how to synchronize the local repository with a remote GitHub repository.

## Activities Performed

* Verified that the local repository was clean.
* Listed all available branches.
* Verified the configured remote repository.
* Understood the Git pull and Git push workflow.
* Prepared the Week-6 project for uploading into the existing GitHub repository.
* Learned the correct approach for pushing changes from the main project repository.

## Git Concepts Learned

* Remote repository
* Git pull
* Git push
* Remote synchronization
* Repository maintenance
* Best practices for updating GitHub



